column19:
Think of the most competitive situation you've been in during the past 12 months. It could be a project, organization, job, or event that felt competitive — where people around you were trying to get ahead and beat each other, rather than working together.
This situation may have brought out the worst in people, causing fairness and generosity to take a backseat to selfishness, winning, and even manipulation or sabotage. This should be a situation where you were personally involved.
In the space below, please write a few sentences describing this situation.
column20:
Think of the most cooperative situation you've been in during the past 12 months. It could be a project, organization, job, or event that felt cooperative — with people working together, trusting one another, and acting with generosity and honesty.
This situation may have brought out the best in people, with everyone working toward a common goal; instead of being selfish, people helped each other. This should be a situation where you were personally involved.
In the space below, please write a few sentences describing this situation.

column20: The most cooperative situation I have encountered in the past 12 months were the floods in Germany. I was involved in this situation for almost 5 weeks until I had to return to the U.S.
column23: Everyone bailed water, organized food, created sand sack dams to prevent water flowing back into cities. In the aftermath, the helpers were engaged in clearing out debris and cleaning homes and streets after the floods had started to recede.

column19: The most competitive situation that I've been in in the past 12 months was when I was auditioning for a play at a local professional theater in town. The nature of the audition process is inherently competitive, but this play was very popular so there were people there that don't usually audition for things and were very nervous which generally reveals our insecurities in interesting ways. Some people that I knew in the past were there but acting differently towards me, some who were talkative towards me in the past weren't, some behaved differently in other ways. The number of roles was limited so there was that kind of killer instinct energy in the room and even made my usually garrulous self withdraw and focus on the audition pieces we had to prepare as opposed to being my normal friendly self. Being that this was one of the first plays being produced by the theater post COVID didn't help as people were rusty from not auditioning and trying to reintroduce/prove themselves to the auditioners.
column23: They weren't necessarily shredding people's audition sides or anything, but it was just a general air of people trying to be very professional and "on their game" which manifested itself into a very competitive vibe in the room. It was more an energy thing than actionable things, so it's hard to explain. But it was definitely felt by me who even pre pandemic is always chatty and less stressed than most, I could feel the difference in the room.

column20: We had all available people in the area called into the office to help clean up after a major IT issue wiped some of our stuff. No one wanted to be there, or redo a bunch of work, but people brought food and it wasn't too bad once we got everything taken care of.

column19: It seems like this describes every hot NFT drop on the WAX blockchain, super competitive where everyone tries to win and there is no collaboration. One recent drop was the Funko Nickelodeon drop which has six different redeemable Funko Pops! Most people I know now who want to collect the Pops do not open the packs they buy on the drop. Rather they sell the packs for a profit then buy the specific NFTs they want, especially the redeemable ones. The competition comes from "sweeping the floor" in which everyone tries to buy the lowest priced packs to keep the "floor price" from falling below a certain level so they can then sell those packs for a bigger profit. There are also those who wait for the floor sweeping then try to buy the packs as low as possible. Of course there are many people who open their packs to see if they have any redeemable Funko Pop NFTs. It is not usually easy to get a pack on the drop and can also be difficult to snag a pack after market as the floor is continually swept.
column23: They try to accumulate as many packs as possible for the lowest price so as the redemption period nears they can sell those packs for the maximum profit. People also try to keep the after-market price of the redeemable NFTs high to maximize their profit potential.
